{
  "Which of the following is required for natural selection to occur?": "",
  "The population must be very small": "",
  "All individuals in a population must be genetically identical": "",
  "Heritable variation must exist among individuals in a population": "",
  "Mutations must occur in every generation": "",
  "Natural selection requires heritable variation among individuals, differential survival and reproduction based on those traits, and that the traits are passed to offspring. Without variation, selection cannot act.": "",
  "Genetic drift has the greatest effect on:": "",
  "Large populations with high genetic diversity": "",
  "Populations with no mutations occurring": "",
  "Small populations where chance events can significantly alter allele frequencies": "",
  "Populations experiencing strong directional selection": "",
  "Genetic drift is the random change in allele frequencies due to chance events. Its effects are most pronounced in small populations because random fluctuations have a proportionally larger impact on allele frequencies.": "",
  "Gene flow occurs when:": "",
  "Organisms within a population mate randomly": "",
  "Alleles are transferred between populations through migration and interbreeding": "",
  "DNA is replicated within a cell": "",
  "A population experiences a natural disaster": "",
  "Gene flow is the movement of alleles between populations through the migration of individuals or their gametes. It tends to reduce genetic differences between populations and can introduce new alleles.": "",
  "Which type of selection favors individuals at both extremes of a phenotypic range over those with intermediate phenotypes?": "",
  "Sexual selection": "",
  "Directional selection": "",
  "Stabilizing selection": "",
  "Disruptive selection": "",
  "Disruptive selection favors individuals at both extremes of a trait distribution and selects against intermediate phenotypes. This can lead to a bimodal distribution and may eventually contribute to speciation.": "",
  "The founder effect is an example of:": "",
  "Natural selection": "",
  "Genetic drift": "",
  "Gene flow": "",
  "The founder effect occurs when a small group establishes a new population with allele frequencies that differ from the original population. It is a form of genetic drift because the change in allele frequencies results from chance sampling.": "",
  "What is the ultimate source of all new genetic variation?": "",
  "Mutation": "",
  "Mutation is the only mechanism that creates entirely new alleles. While sexual reproduction and gene flow reshuffle existing alleles, all genetic variation ultimately traces back to mutations in DNA.": "",
  "Stabilizing selection tends to:": "",
  "Shift the average phenotype in one direction": "",
  "Increase the range of phenotypes in a population": "",
  "Reduce variation by favoring intermediate phenotypes": "",
  "Eliminate all phenotypes equally": "",
  "Stabilizing selection favors individuals with intermediate phenotypes and selects against extreme variants. This reduces phenotypic variation and is the most common form of selection, maintaining the status quo for well-adapted traits.": "",
  "Which of the following is NOT a mechanism of evolution?": "",
  "Homeostasis": "",
  "Homeostasis is the maintenance of stable internal conditions within an organism, not a mechanism of evolution. The four main mechanisms of evolution are mutation, natural selection, genetic drift, and gene flow.": "",
  "Sexual selection can lead to the evolution of traits that:": "",
  "Always increase survival ability": "",
  "Have no effect on reproduction": "",
  "Reduce survival but increase mating success": "",
  "Only appear in females": "",
  "Sexual selection can favor traits that increase an individual's success in mating even if those traits decrease survival, such as the elaborate tail of a peacock, which attracts mates but may make the bird more visible to predators.": "",
  "The bottleneck effect results from:": "",
  "A drastic reduction in population size that randomly changes allele frequencies": "",
  "An increase in mutation rates": "",
  "Preferential mating between individuals with similar traits": "",
  "A large population splitting into two equal groups": "",
  "The bottleneck effect occurs when a population is drastically reduced by a catastrophic event. The surviving population has allele frequencies determined by chance, and genetic diversity is typically reduced.": "",
  "What is 'fitness' in an evolutionary context?": "",
  "An organism's ability to survive and produce viable, fertile offspring relative to others in the population": "",
  "The physical strength and endurance of an organism": "",
  "The total number of offspring an organism produces regardless of survival": "",
  "How long an organism lives": "",
  "Evolutionary fitness (Darwinian fitness) measures an organism's reproductive success relative to others in the population. It is not about strength but about contributing alleles to the next generation through surviving, fertile offspring.": "",
  "What does 'genetic drift' mean?": "",
  "The intentional breeding of organisms for desired traits": "",
  "The gradual accumulation of beneficial mutations over time": "",
  "The movement of organisms from one habitat to another": "",
  "Random changes in allele frequencies in a population due to chance events rather than selection": "",
  "Genetic drift is the random fluctuation of allele frequencies from generation to generation due to chance sampling in reproduction, independent of the alleles' effects on fitness. It is most significant in small populations.": "",
  "What does 'directional selection' mean?": "",
  "Selection that favors individuals at one extreme of a phenotypic range, shifting the population mean over time": "",
  "Selection that favors the average phenotype in a population": "",
  "Selection that favors both extremes of a phenotypic range equally": "",
  "Selection that randomly eliminates individuals from a population": "",
  "Directional selection consistently favors individuals at one end of a phenotypic range, causing the population's trait distribution to shift in that direction over time, such as antibiotic resistance increasing in bacterial populations.": "",
  "What is 'gene flow'?": "",
  "The loss of alleles due to genetic drift": "",
  "The transfer of alleles between populations due to migration or movement of gametes": "",
  "The flow of genetic information from DNA to RNA to protein": "",
  "The process of DNA replication during cell division": "",
  "Gene flow (also called migration in genetics) is the transfer of alleles from one population to another through movement of individuals or their gametes. It tends to homogenize allele frequencies between connected populations.": "",
  "What does 'bottleneck effect' mean?": "",
  "The process of speciation through geographic isolation": "",
  "The preferential survival of the most fit individuals in a population": "",
  "A gradual increase in genetic diversity over many generations": "",
  "A dramatic reduction in population size that causes a loss of genetic diversity and random changes in allele frequencies": "",
  "The bottleneck effect is a form of genetic drift that occurs when a population is sharply reduced in size by a catastrophic event. The surviving population may have very different allele frequencies from the original and reduced genetic diversity.": "",
  "What is the 'founder effect'?": "",
  "The process by which the first mutation in a gene becomes fixed in the population": "",
  "The tendency for founders of new companies to pass traits to their employees": "",
  "A form of genetic drift in which a small group colonizes a new area and the new population's allele frequencies differ from the source population": "",
  "The effect of the environment on gene expression in founding populations": "",
  "The founder effect occurs when a few individuals colonize a new habitat and establish a population with allele frequencies that differ from the original population due to the small, non-representative sample of alleles they carry.": "",
  "What does 'stabilizing selection' mean?": "",
  "Natural selection that favors intermediate phenotypes and acts against extreme variants, reducing phenotypic variation": "",
  "Selection that stabilizes the population size at a constant number": "",
  "The process of maintaining genetic equilibrium through random mating": "",
  "Selection that only acts on organisms in stable environments": "",
  "Stabilizing selection narrows the range of variation by selecting against extreme phenotypes. A classic example is human birth weight, where infants of intermediate weight have the highest survival rates.": "",
  "What does 'disruptive selection' mean?": "",
  "Selection that disrupts the normal reproduction of an organism": "",
  "The breakdown of natural selection due to environmental changes": "",
  "Selection that only occurs during natural disasters": "",
  "Natural selection that favors individuals at both extremes of a trait and selects against intermediate phenotypes": "",
  "Disruptive selection favors extreme phenotypes at both ends of a distribution while selecting against the intermediate form. This can produce a bimodal distribution and may ultimately promote speciation if the extremes become reproductively isolated.": "",
  "What is 'sexual selection'?": "",
  "The artificial selection of organisms for breeding purposes": "",
  "The selection of sex-linked genes during meiosis": "",
  "A form of natural selection in which individuals with certain traits have greater success in attracting mates and reproducing": "",
  "The process by which organisms choose their sex during development": "",
  "Sexual selection is a form of natural selection where traits that increase mating success are favored, even if they decrease survival. It includes intrasexual competition (contests between same-sex individuals) and intersexual selection (mate choice).": "",
  "What does 'natural selection' mean?": "",
  "Any change in a population over time regardless of the cause": "",
  "The human-directed breeding of organisms for desired traits": "",
  "The differential survival and reproduction of individuals based on heritable traits that confer advantages in a given environment": "",
  "The random changes in allele frequencies from generation to generation": "",
  "Natural selection is the process in which organisms with heritable traits better suited to their environment tend to survive and reproduce more successfully, passing those advantageous traits to future generations.": "",
  "A population of beetles lives on a rocky hillside. Brown beetles blend in with the rocks while green beetles are easily spotted by birds. Over ten generations, the frequency of green beetles drops from 50% to 5%. Which mechanism of evolution is primarily responsible?": "",
  "Mutation, because green beetles mutated into brown beetles": "",
  "Gene flow, because green beetles migrated away from the population": "",
  "Natural selection, because predation creates differential survival based on body color": "",
  "Genetic drift, because the green allele was randomly lost": "",
  "This is directional natural selection. Birds preferentially prey on the more visible green beetles, giving brown beetles a survival advantage. Over generations, the allele for brown coloring increases in frequency while the green allele decreases.": "",
  "A hurricane destroys 90% of a lizard population on a small island. The surviving 10% happen to have a higher proportion of blue-tailed individuals than the original population. What mechanism of evolution is at work?": "",
  "Natural selection favoring blue tails for hurricane survival": "",
  "Gene flow from a neighboring island population": "",
  "The bottleneck effect, a form of genetic drift where the surviving population has different allele frequencies by chance": "",
  "Sexual selection favoring blue-tailed lizards": "",
  "The bottleneck effect occurred because the catastrophic event (hurricane) randomly reduced the population, and the survivors' allele frequencies differ from the original population by chance, not because blue tails conferred any survival advantage during the hurricane.": "",
  "In a forest ecosystem, medium-sized seeds are scarce but small and large seeds are abundant. A bird population in this forest feeds on seeds. Over time, birds with very small beaks and very large beaks survive better than birds with medium-sized beaks. What type of selection is occurring?": "",
  "Directional selection toward larger beaks": "",
  "Stabilizing selection favoring average beak size": "",
  "Disruptive selection favoring extreme beak sizes over intermediate ones": "",
  "Artificial selection by researchers": "",
  "This is disruptive selection because the environmental conditions (abundant small and large seeds, scarce medium seeds) favor both extremes of beak size over the intermediate phenotype. Birds with small or large beaks can efficiently exploit available food sources.": "",
  "A small group of birds is blown to an uninhabited island during a storm. This founding population has a much higher frequency of red feathers than the mainland population. After many generations, the island population remains mostly red-feathered. Which evolutionary concept explains this?": "",
  "The founder effect, because the small colonizing group carried a non-representative sample of alleles from the source population": "",
  "Gene flow from the mainland maintaining the red allele": "",
  "Natural selection on the island favors red feathers": "",
  "Convergent evolution with other red-feathered island species": "",
  "The founder effect is a type of genetic drift. The small founding group carried a disproportionately high frequency of the red feather allele, and this initial allele frequency persisted in the new population independent of any selective advantage.": "",
  "In a hospital, a doctor prescribes an antibiotic for a bacterial infection. Most bacteria die, but a few with a pre-existing resistance allele survive and reproduce. Within weeks, the patient's infection returns, and the bacteria are now resistant to the antibiotic. What mechanism of evolution occurred?": "",
  "The bacteria intentionally mutated to become resistant": "",
  "Gene flow introduced resistance alleles from another species": "",
  "Genetic drift randomly caused the resistance allele to increase": "",
  "Natural selection favored bacteria with the pre-existing resistance allele, increasing its frequency in the population": "",
  "The antibiotic created a strong selective pressure. Bacteria with the pre-existing resistance allele survived and reproduced, while susceptible bacteria were killed. This is directional selection, increasing the frequency of the resistance allele in the population.": "",
  "Male peacocks have elaborate, colorful tails that make them more conspicuous to predators. However, males with the most impressive tails tend to mate more often. How do biologists explain the persistence of this seemingly disadvantageous trait?": "",
  "The tail has no effect on survival or reproduction": "",
  "Genetic drift randomly increased the frequency of large tail alleles": "",
  "Sexual selection through female mate choice favors elaborate tails, and the reproductive advantage outweighs the survival cost": "",
  "The tail serves as camouflage in the peacock's natural habitat": "",
  "This is intersexual selection: females preferentially choose males with elaborate tails. The mating advantage of having a large, colorful tail outweighs the survival cost of increased predation risk, maintaining the trait in the population.": "",
  "Two populations of the same squirrel species live on opposite sides of a highway. Individuals rarely cross the highway, and over many generations, genetic analysis shows the populations are diverging. If the highway were removed and squirrels began freely interbreeding again, what evolutionary mechanism would counteract the divergence?": "",
  "Natural selection would immediately make both populations identical": "",
  "Mutation would generate the same new alleles in both populations": "",
  "Genetic drift would cause both populations to become identical by chance": "",
  "Gene flow through interbreeding would mix alleles between populations and reduce genetic differences": "",
  "Gene flow (the movement of alleles between populations through interbreeding) tends to homogenize genetic differences between populations. Resuming interbreeding would introduce alleles from each population into the other, reducing divergence.": "",
  "Human birth weight is subject to a type of selection where babies that are too small or too large have lower survival rates, while babies of intermediate weight have the highest survival. What type of selection is this, and what is its effect on the population?": "",
  "Stabilizing selection, which reduces variation and maintains the average birth weight": "",
  "Directional selection, shifting average birth weight higher over time": "",
  "Sexual selection, which determines which babies are born": "",
  "Disruptive selection, which creates two distinct groups of birth weights": "",
  "This is stabilizing selection, the most common mode of natural selection. By selecting against extreme birth weights (both too low and too high), it reduces variation and maintains the population mean around an optimal value.": "",
  "A researcher studies a population of 10,000 mice and a population of 20 mice over 50 generations. In the small population, one allele was completely lost while in the large population both alleles were maintained. Why did the allele disappear from only the small population?": "",
  "The small population experienced more mutations than the large one": "",
  "Natural selection acted more strongly in the small population": "",
  "The allele was harmful and was eliminated by selection only in the small population": "",
  "Genetic drift caused random loss of the allele, and drift has a much stronger effect in small populations": "",
  "In small populations, genetic drift can cause alleles to be randomly lost or fixed regardless of their fitness effects. In large populations, random fluctuations in allele frequencies are buffered by the large sample size, making complete loss by drift far less likely.": "",
  "Northern elephant seals were hunted nearly to extinction in the 1890s, with only about 20 individuals surviving. Today, the population has recovered to over 100,000, but genetic analyses show extremely low genetic diversity. A biologist proposes that the species is vulnerable to new diseases. What evolutionary concept connects the population history to the current vulnerability?": "",
  "Mutations since the bottleneck have made the seals more susceptible to disease": "",
  "Gene flow from other seal species reduced their genetic diversity": "",
  "The bottleneck effect reduced genetic diversity, and low diversity limits the population's ability to adapt to new pathogens through natural selection": "",
  "Natural selection during hunting specifically eliminated disease-resistance genes": "",
  "The severe population bottleneck in the 1890s drastically reduced genetic diversity through genetic drift. Even though numbers have recovered, the population lacks the genetic variation needed for natural selection to produce resistant individuals when new diseases arise.": ""
}